The Time Tracking Dilemma
text:
Hey there! Our team recently started using time tracking and it's been a bit of a rollercoaster ride. At first, our employees were a bit resistant to the idea, thinking it was a bit old school. But, we gave it a try anyway. Three months in and we haven't seen any major improvements in our product or processes, and it seems like our team is still dragging their feet when it comes to using the tracking system. Some are even underreporting the amount of time they're putting in.

I was curious, have you had any experience with time tracking solutions in a startup environment? Have you seen any positive results from its implementation? We're starting to wonder if it's worth continuing to use time tracking or if we should be looking for other ways to optimize. And if you do think it's worth it, any suggestions on how we can get our team on board and get more accurate data? Thanks in advance!

title: Ask HN: Do you cache/mirror packages on dev machines with Squid or similar?
text:
I know it's relatively common to cache packages for CI, and AWS et al. have solutions for that, but I'm curious if anyone's caching packages locally, on development machines, to speed up image builds etc. when packages have been pulled before?

A big download (or lots of them) in a single layer that ultimately fails, or the reason the layer itself isn't cached is only one small part of it, is annoying, for example. (I'm here writing while waiting for my fourth attempt..)

If so, what're you using? Squid's all I've found. Are you running it on one machine only or for your whole network on/via the router? Any other tips?

title: Ask HN: How can I get into Neurotech as a nontechnical PM in his 30s?
text:
Hi all – I’m in my mid-30s, went to med school but left that track soon after to work as a product manager for early-stage healthtech startups. I’m not an engineer. My skills lie mainly within design and UX.

Throughout my academic years, neuroscience was by far my favorite subject, but I never pursued it fully. With the emergence of Neurotech, I’m feeling that spark again and am looking into paths to get involved in the field.

At this point, would going back to school be of practical value? Given my background, is there a particular discipline that makes most sense – CogSci, Biomedical Eng, Neuroscience, etc? Are there roles in the field for someone with a design / UX skillset?

I’d love any insights / guidance you may have.

Ask HN: Need advice on how to deal with an “AI” project at work I'm opposed to.
text:
A new "high priority project from leadership" is getting started and my team has been asked to work on it. It's nothing illegal or anything but it's using "AI" in a way that I'm personally opposed to.

I've never really worked on anything that "made the world a better place", mostly just boring B2B software. However, I feel like this gets into the category of "making the world a worse place". I honestly just want nothing to do with it.

Normally this seems like it'd be good time to start looking for a new job, but given the current market that seems like it could be a good minute before that happens. Looking for some advice on how to deal with this situation.

Launch HN: Activepieces (YC S22) – Open-Source Zapier Alternative
text:
Hi HN, I’m one of the creators of Activepieces, an open source (MIT) no-code business automation tool. We’re excited to share it with HN! Our Github is https://github.com/activepieces/activepieces, our website is https://www.activepieces.com/ and there’s a video that shows how to build a Pipedrive + Slack + Email flow in 2 minutes at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IY4TI6jGBwM

When we used automation tools like Zapier at my previous job, we found that it became incredibly expensive very quickly, and we had only too few options to self-host business automation when data had to reside on prem.

There are open-source automation tools that we think are too technical like Huginn and Node-RED or developed under less permissive open source licenses like N8n.

So we decided to build an open source automation tool under a permissive license (MIT) with a simple user experience that doesn’t require technical knowledge, and can be self-hosted. We plan to make money from the cloud version and a future enterprise edition with advanced features - maybe advanced roles and permissions.

The current version includes a visual designer for automation flows which can run on schedules (Cron), by Webhooks, or by triggers from external apps—25 apps and counting, including Stripe, Calendly, Google Sheets and others (we’re building these rapidly).

The app is customizable, you can add custom steps using HTTP requests or you can write Node.js code and bring in your npm packages.

If you’re curious about how it works, here are the docs: https://www.activepieces.com/docs

We’d love to hear HN’s thoughts on what we’re building!

Thanks.
